msDesc.head: Canonization Bull, Office for St Birgitta, Sermo angelicus, and Revelations Books 1-8

collation.signatures: Quires 3-14, bottom margin in brown ink, quire signatures.

p.note: Middle of the page in black ink: D. Gustaf Klemm, Dresden 18 Febr. 1837. Next to it in black ink: Köpt till Kongl Bibliotheket Okt 1873 för 44 på auktion i Dresden ankom den 23/10 Gustav Klemming. Below this in pencil, two illegible words (possibly a signature).

Middle of the page by medieval hand in black ink: 1429 ipso die s. Clementis frater Kuch insinuavit processum contra M.W. in valvis ecclesie sancti Severi Erfordensis super executione condempnacionis 87 florenum de camera etc.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Leather over wooden boards. 5 pairs of raised bands and endbands. 2 clasps. Brass plates on with remains of straps and two metal plates on .

: Top edge, tooled and almost illegible: Revelaciones (?); beneath this a fragment of a shelfmark label with illegible text in brown ink. Centre of cover, barely legible tooled shelfmark: C XXX (?), partially covered by an illegible paper label. Bottom left corner: National Library book label.

: paper label: Revelacone (!) S. Brigittae MS. 1424, (written by the same hand as the title and inscription on ); paper label with dark and almost illegible text: Revela[ciones] S. Birgitte (?); part of torn paper lable with illegible text; brown ink on paper label: 57; stamped in gold: A 67.
The pastedowns consist of two bifolia containing a 13th century commentary on the Decretals of Gregory IX; : on Extra 1,38-2,7; 3,21-27; : on Extra 1,8-22; 2,30-3,7.

Regarding the shelfmark label, see Lehmann (1936)
.
binding.condition: Leather torn and faded, possibly originally painted brown. Leather partially missing on and . Boards and endbands visible. Only remnants of the claps remain, brass plates and parts of the straps on . Holes after missing centre and corner bosses on and , as well as two metal plates on . Binding repaired at some point. Board attachement visible on and .

origin.p: Germany Erfurt 1424. According to the colophon on finished on .

provenance.p:
Place of origin or earliest known provenance is the monastery of Saint Peter and Paul (Peterskloster, OSB), Erfurt. The manuscript appears to have been kept at the monastery until the secularisation. It is listed in the monastery’s library catalogue of 1783: De Gotha Joa.: Revelationes approbatae S. Brigittae as no. 57, (cf 57 on the spine), see Theele (1920)
(though the manuscript is not identified by him); also listed in Krämer (1989)
. The manuscript was bought by Friedrich Gottlieb Julius von Bülow zu Beyernaumburg (1760-1831) around after the secularization of the monastery.

The manuscript was then bought by Gustav Klemm (1802-1867), anthropologist and librarian at the royal library in Dresden at the sale of the Bibliotheca Büloviana in . His signature is found on . A catalogue for this sale was made by Georg Heinrich Schäffer whose name is found on .

acquisition.p: Bought at an auction in Dresden by the National Library in , cf. note on .

p.note: Upper margin in black ink by a modern hand: Revelationes S Brigittae. Top right corner in pencil: A. 67. Lower margin in black ink by a modern hand: Bibl. Bülov. Beyern. G. H. Schr. Beneath the right column in brown ink by a medieval hand: amicus simplicitatis 1515 m:o v:c xv et in festo mauricii et cetera Gregorius O beta simplicitas que mansuetudinis et paciencie premio est donanda Simplicitas Est puritas intencionis et innocencia operis and an ownership mark.
In the counterspace of the initial B in brown ink, a mark similar to the ownership mark on .

The manuscript contains quite a lot of additions in the margins, in red, brown and black ink by different medieval hands ranging from one word to longer sentences, also many different manicules (a curious type of double fingered manicule can be seen on ). Some of the additions seem to be corrections or additions made by the scribe or a similar hand, e.g. . Other additions are glosses reacting to the text.
Drawing of woman in red ink; bottom outer margin, a gloss in German.

At the end of the colophon Orate pro scriptore omnes has been supplied with propter deum by a contemporary hand. Two short additions in German and Latin by contemporary hand: Quid deus §Got ist icht got ist nicht ... dass got unbekant ist hec beatus Augustinus episcopus et doctor egregius. §Novum pulcrum exemplum de monacho ordinis sancti benedicti Retulit nobis nuper abbas . . . atque conpassio sepe miraculorum gloria remunerantur Pen drawing and two portraits of monks. The first under the colophon with the name Luckart written above and the second in the outer margin. The second drawing has the text bruder lynkauff written above it.
